		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Trenton</placeName> <date>April 26. 1852</date>.</p>
				<p>My dear sir.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am very much obliged to you<lb/> for your kindness in sending me a copy<lb/> of your translation of <persName>Mendelssohn&#39;s</persName> Trea&#45;<lb/>tise.  Being about to leave town for<lb/> a few days I cannot wait until I<lb/> have recd it&#44; to thank you&#44; but I have<lb/> recd the autobiographical notices in<lb/> the &#34;Introduction&#34; its great interest.<lb/>  If your industry shall not be <hi rend="underline">rever</hi>&#45;<lb/><hi rend="underline">de</hi> as it deserves <del>it</del> to be&#44; it cannot</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>fail&#44; at least&#44; to be <hi rend="underline">admired</hi>&#44; &#38; to re&#45;<lb/>ceive the esteem even of those who differ<lb/> most widely from you as to the object<lb/> to be attained.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is one of the mysteries of the<lb/> Divine Providence at which I would<lb/> most submissively  bow my feeble un&#45;<lb/>derstanding&#44; that the human mind&#44;<lb/> with equal sincerity of heart to know<lb/> the truth from the Scriptures&#44; is so<lb/> diverse in its conclusions.  But<lb/> I would be grateful at the same<lb/> time that the human heart is to</p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p>constitute that such sincere inqui&#45;<lb/>rers&#44; however diverse&#44; may entertain<lb/> a cordial charity &#38; regard towards<lb/> one another.  It is not for the first<lb/> time that I now include you in my<lb/> prayers for myself and all who love<lb/> the revealed truth &#38; wish to under&#45;<lb/>stand &#38; follow it&#44; that we may be<lb/> all guided by the same unerring<lb/> spirit that directed the sacred wri&#45;<lb/>ters.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Very truly &#38; respectfully yours</p>
				<p><persName role="author">John Hall</persName>.</p>
		</body>
